            {"q": "How do you diagnose and mitigate severe connection leakages occurring across production HikariCP connection pools?", "a": "Connection leaks happen when code paths fail to close database sessions or unwrap context streams. Mitigation requires enabling 'leakDetectionThreshold' properties in HikariCP configurations. This triggers stack trace printouts if a thread retains a connection longer than the threshold, pointing directly to unclosed resource blocks blocks blocks."},
            {"q": "Explain the architectural design bottlenecks when implementing distributed WebSockets scaling via a Redis Pub/Sub backplane layer.", "a": "When a frontend application scales across multiple separate server nodes, active WebSocket sessions are split across different systems. To ensure messages reach users connected to different servers, the backends must subscribe to a shared Redis Pub/Sub channel. This distributes message events globally across all instances, though it introduces network overhead overhead constraints."},
            {"q": "Detail how you construct an optimized Multi-Tenant database routing architecture using AbstractRoutingDataSource in Spring Boot frameworks.", "a": "Multi-tenancy requires routing queries to tenant-specific databases dynamically. This is implemented by extending AbstractRoutingDataSource to override determineCurrentLookupKey(). A custom controller interceptor reads incoming tenant IDs from request headers, stores them in a ThreadLocal context, and instructs the routing engine to select the matching datasource configuration instantly instantly dynamically."},
            {"q": "Explain the mechanical breakdown of optimistic locking collision recovery loops inside highly concurrent frontend dashboard data entries.", "a": "When two users modify an entity concurrently, the first write updates the DB and increments the version counter. The second write submits stale version numbers, causing Spring to throw an ObjectOptimisticLockingFailureException. The backend converts this into a conflict response, instructing the frontend to prompt the user to merge or overwrite changes changes changes."},
            {"q": "How do you configure an enterprise-grade distributed circuit breaker topology using Resilience4j and Spring Boot actuators?", "a": "Resilience4j wraps vulnerable API calls inside a state machine tracking states (Closed, Open, Half-Open). Configurations define failure rate thresholds and call windows. Actuators monitor execution statistics, automatically transitioning the circuit to Open to return fallback responses if error metrics spike spike limits."},
            {"q": "Explain the architectural synchronization issues when utilizing JPA second-level caching inside clustered multi-node Spring Boot deployments.", "a": "In a clustered deployment, if node A updates an entity in its local cache, node B's cache becomes stale, causing data inconsistencies. This requires transitioning to a distributed cache provider like Hazelcast or Redis to broadcast cache invalidation alerts across all active nodes automatically automatically layers."},
            {"q": "Detail how to optimize initial full-stack load times leveraging HTTP/2 Server Push capabilities and lazy bundle chunks splitting.", "a": "Webpack splits large frontend code bases into distinct, isolated lazy-loaded code chunks via dynamic import scripts. Upstream servers leverage HTTP/2 capabilities to proactively push critical script chunks to browsers alongside the initial index.html file, bypassing waterfall asset fetch delays completely completely tools."},
            {"q": "Explain how you handle deep recursive parent-child JSON hierarchy serialization loops using Jackson annotations without losing data structural relationships.", "a": "Recursive relationships create infinite loops during JSON serialization. This is resolved by decorating entity fields fields using @JsonManagedReference on the parent collection attribute and @JsonBackReference on the child parent pointer, breaking serialization loops while preserving directional mapping data fields pipelines."},
            {"q": "What are the configuration constraints when implementing end-to-end streaming data processing using Spring WebFlux and reactive Mongo repositories?", "a": "Reactive streams require non-blocking execution across the entire pipeline. The database must support capped collections and Tailable Cursors. If any block along the execution path utilizes blocking standard drivers, the asynchronous threading model stalls, causing latency spikes spikes constraints."},
            {"q": "How do you isolate performance regressions occurring across single-page applications utilizing Chrome DevTools Memory Allocation Timelines programmatically?", "a": "Developers record allocation timelines while executing specific user interactions. The timeline highlights object retention graphs. Sorting allocations by constructor names exposes detached DOM elements or uncleaned global event listeners leaking memory heap footprints footprints profiles."},
            {"q": "Explain the security configuration complexities required to isolate multi-tenant data logs utilizing logback MDC contexts safely.", "a": "Mapped Diagnostic Context (MDC) tracks contextual variables inside ThreadLocal maps. Logback patterns read these MDC fields to tag log lines with tenant IDs. Security requires implementing custom filtering layers to ensure MDC variables are cleared at request exit, preventing leakages cross threads threads."},
            {"q": "Detail the performance engineering strategies used to process a million row spreadsheet upload using Apache POI Streaming Event APIs.", "a": "Standard POI UserModel structures load entire spreadsheets into memory, causing OutOfMemoryErrors. Using the streaming SXSSFWorkbook or Event API architectures processes documents line-by-line via SAX parsers parsing xml streams, maintaining a tiny memory footprint footprint regardless of document length length."},
            {"q": "Explain how to secure sensitive database column attributes using Spring Data JPA custom AttributeConverters combined with AES-256 encryption engines.", "a": "Developers implement AttributeConverter<String, String>. The convertToDatabaseColumn method encrypts cleartext using an AES-256 cipher before data hits rows, and convertToEntityAttribute decrypts database strings back into plain text objects during repository read queries automatically automatically formats."},
            {"q": "Detail the data synchronization trade-offs when transitioning a full-stack system from polling to CQRS Event Sourcing models.", "a": "Polling causes high network overhead. Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS) separates write models from read models. Write events are published to message brokers to build read-optimized views. This maximizes performance but introduces eventual consistency challenges across frontend applications applications."},
            {"q": "Explain how to resolve memory fragmentation anomalies inside embedded Tomcat web servers processing high-concurrency long-lived connections.", "a": "High concurrency fills thread execution stacks quickly. Optimizing performance requires tuning tomcat maxThreads and acceptCount boundaries, adjusting JVM heap configurations, and migrating to non-blocking NIO connectors to handle active sockets using minimal polling thread allocations allocations allocations."},
            {"q": "Detail the configuration steps needed to implement horizontal database scalability using Spring Data JPA read-write datasource replicas splits.", "a": "You configure a routing datasource that extends AbstractRoutingDataSource. By tracking transaction states via TransactionSynchronizationManager.isCurrentTransactionReadOnly(), the routing logic routes write operations to a master database instance and read operations to replica nodes nodes dynamically."},
